### H2 Structure (10 H2s — all structured as real user queries or long-tail keywords)

**H2 1: What Is the Actual Difference Between Oval and Almond Nails?**
*Intent: Resolves the #1 pain point immediately. Readers arrive already knowing this is confusing — confirm their experience, then clarify with visual language. Cover: tip shape, degree of taper, base-to-tip width ratio, how they read at a glance. Include the "spectrum" concept: round → oval → almond → stiletto.*

**H2 2: Oval Nails vs Almond Nails Side by Side — The Key Comparison**
*Intent: Give readers the reference comparison they came for. Cover: shape definition, length requirement, taper degree, durability, maintenance level, nail art suitability, who each flatters. This is the comparison table section — but written as prose with clear differentiators, not a generic bullet list.*

**H2 3: Which Nail Shape Makes Your Fingers Look Longer?**
*Intent: Answers one of the top 5 voice search queries. Almond creates stronger elongation; oval creates softer elongation. Both help but differently. Map to finger types.*

**H2 4: Is Oval or Almond Better for Your Finger and Hand Shape?**
*Intent: The personalisation engine of the post. Break down by hand type: short fingers, wide nail beds, narrow nail beds, long fingers, wide palms. Give a clear shape recommendation per profile. Reference celebrity manicurist advice (Jacqueline Pham, NewBeauty Spring 2026) on nail bed width as a deciding factor.*

**H2 5: Do Almond Nails Break More Easily Than Oval Nails?**
*Intent: Directly addresses pain point #3. Honest answer: yes, almond tips concentrate stress at the narrower point; oval distributes force more evenly. But context matters — acrylic or gel overlay changes the equation. Active lifestyles, hand-heavy jobs, and very short natural nails all shift the answer. Conclude with a practical durability verdict per lifestyle.*

**H2 6: Can You Get Almond Nails on Short Natural Nails?**
*Intent: Pain point #2 — length anxiety. Honest threshold: you need enough free edge for the taper to read clearly. Introduce "baby almond" as the 2026 solution for short nail lovers who want almond without length. Compare baby almond visually to oval — where the shapes converge.*

**H2 7: Which Nail Shape Is Better for Nail Art?**
*Intent: Design-led readers need this answered specifically. Oval: best for minimalist, French tips, cat-eye, single-colour, clean line art. Almond: best for ombré, gradient, 3D elements, chrome finishes, tip-focused embellishment. Both work — but the canvas behaves differently. Give concrete design examples for each.*

**H2 8: Which Shape Is More Low-Maintenance for Everyday Wear?**
*Intent: Practical readers (office workers, mums, gym-goers) need a lifestyle verdict. Oval wins for active daily wear — no concentrated stress point, easier filing, more forgiving when a chip happens. Almond requires more symmetry precision and tip care. But oval is not boring — set the record straight.*

**H2 9: Oval or Almond Nails — Which Shape Is More Popular Right Now?**
*Intent: Trend-conscious readers want context. Almond has dominated search and TikTok for several years (Google Trends: almond sits at 60–75 baseline vs oval's 19–32). Baby almond is the 2026 breakout evolution. Oval is having a soft resurgence as part of the "clean girl" and quiet luxury aesthetic. Neither is going anywhere.*

**H2 10: So — Which Nail Shape Is Actually Right for You?**
*Intent: The definitive verdict section. Give a clear recommendation matrix: choose oval if [X], choose almond if [Y], choose baby almond if [Z]. No hedging. This is what the reader came for — give them the answer. Close with a natural link hook to the almond-nails-guide pillar and almond-vs-coffin-nails for readers who are still considering other shapes.*

---

### Structure Reasoning
H2s 1–2 resolve the confusion (what's the actual difference); H2s 3–6 answer the practical decision questions (hand type, durability, length); H2s 7–8 serve the lifestyle and aesthetic reader; H2s 9–10 give trend context and a definitive verdict. This mirrors the reader's actual decision journey from confusion → evaluation → confidence. Every H2 is either a long-tail keyword or a word-for-word user query — the post is built to rank on H2-level searches as well as the primary term.

