## RESEARCH NOTES FOR WRITER

- **The baby almond moment:** In 2026, "baby almond" (short-to-medium almond with subtle taper) is bridging the oval/almond divide. It reads more almond than oval but works on shorter lengths. This is a key differentiator no competitor covers well — Mirellé should own this language.
- **The visual confusion problem is the hook:** Don't open by defining both shapes neutrally. Open by naming the confusion ("from a distance, they look almost identical — and that's the real problem"). This mirrors actual user experience and builds immediate trust.
- **Nail art section is underserved by competitors:** Every ranking post says "both work for nail art" and stops there. Specifying which designs read better on each shape (cat-eye on oval, ombré on almond) is a genuine content gap to fill.
- **Almond dominates search, oval dominates function:** This tension is the editorial spine of the post. Almond is what everyone wants; oval is what most people's lifestyle actually supports. The post should be honest about this.
- **Do not stray into:** tutorial content (that's how-to-shape-almond-nails), inspiration galleries (almond-nail-ideas-2026), or transactional product reviews (press-on-almond-nails). Stay in the comparison lane throughout.
- **Image guidance (research-suggested):** 6–8 images. Must include: a clear side-by-side shape silhouette comparison, hand-type examples (wide nail bed vs narrow), nail art examples on each shape (one oval, one almond), and at least one baby almond example.
